    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6877df4b-ac68-4064-9c52-f10a45cfac8f",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 39-year-old man who appears slightly older than his stated age, with a thin build, mildly disheveled clothing, and inconsistent eye contact. He often scans the room before sitting down and may pause mid-sentence as if distracted by sounds others do not hear. His facial expression is guarded, and his speech can alternate between brief, concrete answers and tangential, loosely connected responses. During periods of stress, he becomes more withdrawn and suspicious, sometimes whispering to himself. He reports intermittent auditory hallucinations, describing critical voices that are most noticeable at night and during times of isolation.\n\nHe lives alone in a small rented apartment and receives intermittent support from his mother and an older sister, though his social network is limited. {patientName} previously worked in warehouse and delivery jobs but has struggled to maintain steady employment over the last several years because of impaired concentration, social mistrust, and inconsistent sleep. He spends much of his day indoors listening to the radio, smoking cigarettes on the balcony, and watching late-night television. He has few close friends and tends to avoid crowded public places because he feels people are talking about him.\n\nHis daily routine is irregular. He often skips breakfast, drinks large amounts of coffee, and smokes about one pack of cigarettes per day. He denies current alcohol misuse but has a remote history of binge drinking in his twenties. He is physically inactive, with weight gain over the past few years related to poor diet and prior antipsychotic treatment. Personal hygiene fluctuates depending on symptom severity; on better days he showers, shaves, and keeps his apartment reasonably organized, while during symptomatic periods dishes accumulate and laundry remains undone.\n\nDespite his illness, {patientName} retains interests that occasionally help ground him. He enjoys sketching city scenes in a notebook, following professional football, and taking short evening walks when he feels safe enough to go outside. He is wary but not overtly hostile, and with time he can become cooperative in conversation. Family members describe him as intelligent and gentle at baseline, noting a gradual decline in functioning since his late twenties with increasing social isolation, suspiciousness, blunted affect, and episodes of hearing voices."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2daae920-7a2e-462f-b3fe-ac151d7ce062",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a several-year history of schizophrenia with progressive decline in social and occupational functioning since his late twenties. He has had two prior psychiatric hospitalizations for worsening paranoia, insomnia, and command auditory hallucinations, most recently three years ago after stopping antipsychotic medication for several months. He reports partial adherence to prior treatment because he disliked sedation and weight gain. There is no known history of seizure disorder, major head trauma, or chronic neurologic illness.\n\nComorbid conditions include nicotine dependence and chronic insomnia associated with psychotic exacerbations. He has no diagnosed diabetes or cardiovascular disease, but he has gained weight during previous treatment courses and requires metabolic monitoring. He underwent an appendectomy in early adulthood without complications. He denies current illicit drug use and says he has not consumed alcohol heavily in years, though collateral history suggests episodic binge drinking in the distant past. He currently lives independently with limited social support, relies on disability income, and often misses outpatient appointments when symptoms worsen."
          }
        ]
      }
